se.jguru.nazgul.core.algorithms.event.api.producer

Class AbstractEventProducer<T extends EventConsumer>

  • java.lang.Object
    • se.jguru.nazgul.core.clustering.api.AbstractClusterable
      • se.jguru.nazgul.core.algorithms.event.api.producer.AbstractEventProducer<T>
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Serializable, EventConsumerWrapper<T>, EventProducer<T>, Clusterable

    public abstract class AbstractEventProducer<T extends EventConsumer>
extends AbstractClusterable
implements EventProducer<T>
    Abstract implementation of the EventProducer interface, sporting Clusterable behaviour. That is - this AbstractEventProducer implementation is intended for use within a cluster.
    Author:
    Lennart Jörelid, jGuru Europe AB
    See Also:

      • registerConsumerToEventProducers

        protected boolean registerConsumerToEventProducers(T validEventConsumer)
        Adds the EventConsumer to its originating EventProducers, by connecting it to the underlying EventGenerator. For example, this is the method where you would call aButton.addActionListener(listener) or equivalent.
        Parameters:
        validEventConsumer - A non-null EventConsumer which has been validated by this EventProducer WRT its ID.
        Returns:
        true if the registration process was successful, and false otherwise.

      • removeConsumerFromEventProducers

        protected boolean removeConsumerFromEventProducers(T validEventConsumer)
        Removes the ListenerType from its proper EventProducers, by removing from the EventGenerator appropriate for the provided ListenerType. For example, this is the method where you would call aButton.removeActionListener(listener) to remove your EventListener from its EventGenerator(s).
        Parameters:
        validEventConsumer - A non-null EventListener which has been validated by this EventProducer WRT its ID.
        Returns:
        true if the removal process was successful, and false otherwise.

      • onConsumerRegistered

        Override this method to provide implementation notifying other AbstractEventProducer working in clustered mode with this one about the newly registered EventConsumer. The default implementation does nothing.
        Parameters:

      • onRemoveNonRegisteredConsumer

        protected boolean onRemoveNonRegisteredConsumer(String senderID,
                                                String eventConsumerID)

        Override this method to provide implementation notifying other AbstractEventProducers working in clustered mode with this one about a remove request for the consumer with the provided consumerID. The intended usage caters for the following situation:

        
 // Create 2 clustered EventProducers
 AbstractEventProducer<SomeEventConsumer> clusteredEventProducer1 = ...
 AbstractEventProducer<SomeEventConsumer> clusteredEventProducer2 = ...

 // Register an EventConsumer
 SomeEventConsumer consumer = ...
 clusteredEventProducer1.addConsumer(anEventConsumer);

 // Remove the EventConsumer from another node in the cluster
 clusteredEventProducer2.removeConsumer(anEventConsumer.getClusterId());

        Here, clusteredEventProducer2 must notify clusteredEventProducer1 about the removeConsumer call and its corresponding ID. ClusteredEventProducer1 removes anEventConsumer from its internal storage. The default implementation of this method does nothing.

        Parameters:
        senderID - The ID of this AbstractEventProducer.
        eventConsumerID - The ID of the EventConsumer to remove.
        Returns:
        true if the EventConsumer with the given ID was removed, and false otherwise.
